
	<sn><md>## Global Pressure Belt{.text-center}

**Wind** is the result of `horizontal differences in air pressure`. Air moves forming winds from areas of **high pressure** to areas of **low pressure**.


:::.row

:::.col-12 .col-lg-7
On the Earth’s surface, pressure belts are broadly classified into two classes:

* **High pressure belt** – region where air pressure is high
* **Low pressure belt** – region where air pressure is low

These pressure belts cover different parts of the Earth’s surface in east–west directions.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-5
![diagram](https://i.imgur.com/bHnJsCP.png)
![diagram](https://kpiasacademy.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/a-close-up-of-a-logo-description-automatically-ge.jpeg)
:::

:::



:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-lg-7
There are **seven semi-permanent global pressure belts** of the surface atmospheric circulation. They are:

* Equatorial low pressure belt
* Sub-tropical high pressure belt (North)
* Sub-tropical high pressure belt (South)
* Sub-polar low pressure belt (North)
* Sub-polar low pressure belt (South)
* Polar high pressure belt (North)
* Polar high pressure belt (South)
:::

